    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-04-27T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-04-27T17:00:00-05:00" n="672"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d672">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">867N.00/450b: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Turkey</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-04-27T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >April 27, 1937—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>26. Deep concern is felt in important Jewish circles in this country over
                    recommendations believed to be contained in the Report of the Royal Commission
                    of Inquiry<note n="2" xml:id="d672fn2">For the appointment of this Commission
                        and its objectives, see despatch No. 2404, July 31, 1936, from the
                        Ambassador in the United Kingdom, <ref target="frus1936v03#pg_445">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, p. 445</ref>.</note> into the recent
                    disorders in Palestine. It is feared that the Report will recommend a complete
                    cessation of Jewish immigration into Palestine or some sort of cantonization of
                    the country. The view has been expressed that a prosperous National Home for the
                    Jews in Palestine will serve as a stabilizing factor in the region of the
                    Eastern Mediterranean and that it would therefore be in the interest of Turkey
                    to give moral support to the development of the National Home.</p>
                <p>I would appreciate your considered opinion as to whether views in the above sense
                    would be favorably received by Atatürk<note n="3" xml:id="d672fn3">Kemal
                        Atatürk, President of Turkey.</note> if you were instructed to seek an
                    audience for that purpose.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
